commit f287ee74246f12e46249ac58be6b27671cdaf2fb
Author: Scott Schneider <scottas@meta.com>
Date:   Wed Apr 8 16:33:24 2026 -0700

    Replace shared_ptr singleton with Meyers singleton in CuptiCallbackApi (#1350)

    Summary:
    Pull Request resolved: https://github.com/pytorch/kineto/pull/1350

    `CuptiCallbackApi::singleton()` returns `std::shared_ptr<CuptiCallbackApi>` by
    value. Every call copies the shared_ptr, incurring two atomic ref-count
    operations (increment on copy, decrement on destruction). The
    `callback_switchboard` function -- the CUPTI hot path fired on every
    `cudaLaunchKernel` -- calls `singleton()` on each invocation. On ARM/aarch64,
    atomic operations are more expensive than on x86 due to load-exclusive /
    store-exclusive barriers, making this overhead measurable during profiling.

    This diff changes `singleton()` to return `CuptiCallbackApi&` from a Meyers
    singleton (`static CuptiCallbackApi instance`), eliminating the per-call atomic
    overhead. This matches the pattern already used by `CuptiActivityApi::singleton()`.

    **SIOF safety analysis:**

    D39942067 / PR #661 introduced the `shared_ptr` to fix a SIOF crash on aarch64. We
    analyzed all static initialization dependencies and found:

    1. `CuptiCallbackApi`'s constructor is `= default` with all trivially
       constructible members. It has zero static dependencies at construction time.

    2. The actual SIOF was between `initCallbackApi()` and GLOG -- there is an
       explicit comment in the code: "TODO: Remove temporarily to work around
       static initialization order issue between this and GLOG." The problematic
       `LOG()` call was already commented out as a workaround.

    3. The `shared_ptr` does not meaningfully fix SIOF: no caller stores the
       `shared_ptr` long-term, so the lifetime-extension property is never used.
       Both the `shared_ptr` static and a Meyers singleton have identical
       construction timing (first call) and destruction timing (static destruction).

    4. A Meyers singleton is safe here because `CuptiCallbackApi()` has no
       dependencies on other statics. The SIOF risk is in `initCallbackApi()`
       (which calls CUPTI and potentially GLOG), not in singleton construction.

    Reviewed By: ryanzhang22

    Differential Revision: D99843809

