    refactor JSON chrome trace writing (#1342)

    Summary:
    Pull Request resolved: https://github.com/pytorch/kineto/pull/1342

    Refactors JSON writing in `ChrometraceLogger`. The general principles here:

    1. Centralize writing JSON string as much as possible. We define families of `write*Event()` functions and then call those when we need to write an actual event. There are still some one-off JSON string writing, but the structured events are centralized in helper functions.
    2. Call out, through comments, some of the structure that gets buried in the strings. That is, it's easy to miss an opening `[` or a trailing `,` which are important for the structure.
    3. Make the logic that can't be centralized as boring as possible.

    There's still probably more refactoring we can do. Note that it's not possible to truly centralize everything as we actually store a lot of metadata as JSON in our data structures. Trace down `getMetadataValue()` and `metadataJson()` to see more on that.

    Regarding performance, when running our benchmark at `benchmarks/json_output_benchmarks.cpp`, we're basically the same:
    ```
    ==== small scenario, 3 runs
    main:    1.27 MB/s, 2.59 MB/s, 2.44 MB/s
    this PR: 1.98 MB/s, 2.50 MB/s, 2.41 MB/s

